The Peoples Democratic Party, PDP, has concluded its National Assembly primary elections with the party failing to field aspirants for two senatorial seats in the three senatorial districts in the state. Speaking on the outcomes of the party primary elections, the National Secretary of the Congress Committee, Sani MB Ahmad, said the party had conducted peaceful elections although some House of Representatives also did not field aspirants for the election. Although Sani MB Ahmad, refused to reveal the two senatorial seats still vacant, reports have it that Kano, South and North are the ones having this problem. Similarly, some local governments did not have House of Representatives aspirants, something that created a serious vacuum in the primaries. When asked which faction Sani MB Ahmad is representing, he said categorically that he was sent from Abuja to observe the elections which he has done. He assured that the elections they conducted were peaceful and with Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC), Department of State Services (DSS), Police and other stakeholdersâ€™ participation, which made it authentic, adding that they would submit their reports to Abuja. Wada Sagagi, a factional chairman, was barred by the court from parading himself as the chairman of the party, pending the determination of substantive suits filed by Ambassador Aminu Wali faction challenging his leadership. When contacted, Wada Sagagi told our correspondent that he was having a court action as such he was not the one who organized the elections but the local government chairmen of the party